<p><i>Out On the Hills</i> by Peggy Lee Napier</p>  

<p>If Tom Sawyer or David Copperfield had been girls, they would probably have been Deenie O’Loughlin of Peggy Lee Napier’s Out on the Hills. A young narrator from the seclusion of West Virginia in the innocent days of the late 1940s could not be more naïve than Deenie. In an authentic Appalachian voice that stirred echoes of my paternal grandmother, Deenie tells her story with honesty and immediacy.</p>

<p>And what a story!</p>

<p>In tales of one-room schoolhouse days, bucolic meanderings through the hills and Sunday mornings of fervent worship, Deenie praising God with a stringed instrument as her sister sings, Napier’s heroine sets the stage for an adventure so harrowing it could never have been foreseen. Father is out of town and his return is repeatedly delayed. The aunt who cares for Deenie and her sister, Ilse, is called away to attend to her suddenly ill sister. The offer from a traveling preacher to feature Deenie and Ilse in his revival tour seems both providential and promising.</p>

<p>What transpires will mark the end of innocence for Deenie: what she witnesses teaches her that people are not always as they present themselves, that trust can be placed too precipitately.</p>

<p>Portraying unscrupulous people who prey on the ignorant but faithful, Napier skillfully contrasts them with Deenie and her child-like faith. She is careful not to cast into doubt the faith of the hill people because they are susceptible to the machinations of skillful con artists. Their faith is seen to be genuine because of their fervor, their charity and their love for one another. Napier even manages to work in Good Samaritans, outcasts who come to Deenie’s rescue in her most desperate hour.</p>

<p>Out On the Hills is one of those books that leaves you with a warm glow for a while after you’re done, a feel-good read that you will recommend to your friends, as I recommend it to you. Friendship and family, adventure and restoration – as satisfying a recipe for a story as any I know.</p>

